<font color="#FF0000">THE GIFT THAT KEEP ON GIVING</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct 31  5:53:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
PTSD is one of those things that you really don't know what it is or how to handle it even after someone tells you that you have it, because you see yourself as quite normal while you swing between pairs of opposites, go pasive-agressive, or go hide with recurrent depression.<br><br>
It has taken me several years just to understand this and admit to myself that I am stuck with it. It is not true denial. Reality shifts all over the place, and however I may be from moment to moment, it is all very real to me, even if it is contradictory to someone else. Justification and common sense is also very distorted. <br><br>
This is the part that my wife of 26 years has the most difficulty. I know now underneath it all is the real me, and the real me now knows how to make an appearance more often than not. It will continue to be very hard work for as long as I live, but being &quot;me&quot; is worth it! <br><br>
There is help, and real hope out there for both sides. Just remember that we are all victims and survivors at the same time.<br><br>
The Vietnam War may be physically over, but it still lives in our minds. <br><br>
PTSD, the gift that keeps on giving! <br><br>
--Art 
